 and sustainable forests growing hardwoods for barbecue pits. They talk to pit masters and proprietors, who share the secrets of barbecue in their own words. Like side dishes to the first-person stories, short essays by the authors explore a myriad of barbecue's themes—food history, manliness and meat, technology, nostalgia, civil rights, small-town Texas identity, barbecue's connection to music, favorite drinks such as Big Red, Dr. Pepper, Shiner Bock, and Lone Star beer—to mention only a few. An ode to Texas barbecue in films, a celebration of sports and barbecue, and a pie chart of the desserts that accompany brisket all find homes in the sidebars of the book, while photographic portraits of people and places bring readers face-to-face with the culture of barbecue.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2022) 0aBarbecuingzSouthern StatesvAnecdotes. 0aBarbecuingzSouthern States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aAbrahams, Marsha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBendele, Marvin C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenke, Gavin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBusch, Andrew M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCovey, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCroke, Dave, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdge, John T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEngelhardt, Elizabeth S. D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaupt, Melanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKocurek, Carly A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPowell, Lisa Jordan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabula